@manual{Sampling,
    title = {{For the chosen time step and number of steps, the frequency range we can obtain for the VDOS is (3, 3.3$\times10^4$)cm$^{-1}$  (from the Nyquist criterion). 
It is reasonable to analyze vibrations of water molecules whose frequencies are in (1600, 3800)cm$^{-1}$.
To obtain the vibrations with the highest frequecies $\nu_\text{max}$, the sampling rates $f_{s}$ must be at least as high as $f_s=2\nu_\text{max}$, thus, the time step $\Delta{t}$ must satisfy $\Delta{t}\leq{1}/{2\nu_\text{max}}$.
   If $f_{s}$ is known, the upper bound of vibrational frequencies $\nu_\text{max}$ can be calculated.
   For a sequence with $M$ steps, the maximun period $T_\text{max}=\Delta{t}$ (the maximum frequency ${f_s}_\text{max}=1/{\Delta{t}}$).
   $f_{s_\text{max}}=2\nu_\text{max}$, then $\nu_\text{max}={f_s}_\text{max}/{2}=1/{2\Delta{t}}$.
   In our simulation, the time step is 0.5 fs and the total number of steps $M\approx10^4$. Thus the frequency range of the VDOS is in $(3.3, 3.3\times 10^4)$ cm$^{-1}$.
   In this thesis, we consider the vibrational modes of water molecules in (1600, 3800) cm$^{-1}$.
